            . I am servant to Mr. Wm. Hobson, who lives in <placeName id="t18270913-243-crimeloc1374">Windsor-place, City-road</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18270913-243-crimeloc1374" type="placeName" value="Windsor-place, City-road"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18270913-243-crimeloc1374" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18270913-243-off1372 t18270913-243-crimeloc1374"></join>. On the 14th of July the prisoner came into the kitchen; he went out in about eight minutes, and I immediately missed seven spoons, which were safe about five minutes before. I had been out of the kitchen while he was there - I knew him before; master had employed him to scour some empty houses down; we could not find him till the Monday following, when he was taken.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18270913-243-person2039">
                  HENRY 
                  CHERRY
               <interp inst="t18270913-243-person2039" type="surname" value="CHERRY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-243-person2039" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-243-person2039" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an errand-boy to Mr. Hobson. I heard of this loss, and met the prisoner on the Thursday following. I asked what he had done with the spoons; he said they were sold and melted down, and they could not have them any more. I said Mr. Hobson would have him taken - he said he did not care; he could not give him more than six weeks, for he did not break any locks.</p>
